1. Controlling Bulk DensityBiomass like paddy straw or wood chips is "fluffy." If you measure a loose pile of straw, it’s mostly air. If you pack it down, it’s mostly straw.

The Problem:
The Agreto HFM II probe and your NIR/IR sensors are affected by how many particles are packed into their field of view.

The Solution:
By using a fixed 10L volume, you can weigh the bucket to calculate the density ($\rho = \text{mass} / 10\text{L}$).
This allows you to say: "At a density of $X$, this moisture reading is $Y$." 
Without the bucket, your data will be "noisy" because the density changes every time you move the straw.

2. The Agreto Probe’s "Compression Requirement"The Agreto HFM II is a conductivity/capacitance probe. For it to work, the biomass must be in tight contact with the metal tip of the 50cm probe.If you stick the probe into a loose pile, there are air gaps between the straw and the sensor, leading to a falsely low moisture reading.
In a 10L bucket, you can compress the material consistently (e.g., "compress until the bucket is full") to ensure the probe is surrounded by a dense, uniform sample.

3. Creating a "Uniform Surface" for your SensorsYour MLX90614 and NIR sensors need a flat, consistent surface to look at.In a 10L bucket, the top surface of the biomass can be leveled off.This keeps the Distance (Z-axis) between your ESP32 board and the biomass constant. As we discussed earlier, if the distance changes, the light intensity changes, which ruins your calibration.
Representative SamplingA handful of straw might be unusually wet or dry. A 10L sample is large enough to be "statistically representative" of the entire truckload or batch provided by the startup.
